title: For Sale:  S&W Smith & Wesson 396 Night Guard 44 Spl
postcontent: Very Nice Rare S&W 396 .44 spl. in as new condition with it's original box with all the original paperwork. That is not a scratch above the cylinder release thumb piece. It is a factory arrow on all 396s. These guns were made a very short time only due to the unpopularity of the caliber at the time due to the .44 magnum. Now they are popular and hard to find. The 396 I'm told was made for only 9 months. I called S&W and they have no plans to make more. Most people don't know that S&W made a .44 Spl on the L frame and as the word gets out these guns will become even more sought after and very rare. Try to find another one for sale even now. I like that the 396 NG .44 Spl. has a steel barrel and steel cylinder unlike the other S&W Night Guard models which have alloy cylinders. I have a 396 that I shoot and can verify they are fantastic weapons that I won't be without

title: For Sale:  Excellent WWII Springfield M1 Garand c. 1943
postcontent: This is an excellent condition and all correct WWII Springfield M1 Garand Rifle. The serial number on this M1 is 1647185, which places its date of manufacture in June 1943. The barrel is the original Springfield barrel that is also dated June of 1943. The bore is shiny and the muzzle gauges at less than 1! The throat erosion is also excellent at 1.0, so this rifle has been fired very sparingly and it will be an excellent shooter. The Barrel retains almost all of its original parkerized finish. The Rear Sight has a correct Type 1C Elevation Knob, which is knurled, with closed arrowheads, a Type 2B Lock Bar and Type 2 Rear Sight Cover. The Bolt is a correct -12 SA Springfield bolt with the majority of the original parkerized finish. The Operating Rod is a correct Type 5, 6SA un-cut op rod. The Follower Rod is a correct Type 4 "short fork" with the ribbed end riveted. The Operating Rod catch is a correct Type 2. The Follower Arm is a correct Type 4 with rounded shoulders. The Follower is a correct Type 2C with appropriate "11" mark. The Bullet Guide is a correct Type 3 with wide slot. The Trigger Housing is a correct Type 8, -12 SA marked. The Trigger Guard is the correct Type 1G that is milled. The Trigger is a correct Type 2 with no tooling hole. The Hammer is a correct Type 2C, -3SA marked hammer. The Hammer Spring Plunger is a correct Type 1 with no rim on the sides. The Hammer Spring Housing is a correct Type 2. The Safety is a correct Type 3B, -9SA marked. The Gas Cylinder is a correct Type 2B that is appropriately unmarked and which has the majority of its original black finish. The Gas Cylinder Lock is a correct Type 1 with chamfered front face with the majority of its original parkerized finish. The Gas Lock Screw is a correct Type 1 Single Slot. The receiver still has the majority of its original finish. The rifle sits in its original WWII Springfield Stock that has a crisp SA/EMcF Cartouche on the left side, which is the correct cartouche for this serial number, and a circle "P" firing proof on the bottom. The stock has a beautiful original finish and has no cracks noted and only has normal dings and small scratches, probably from storage as I do not think this rifle was ever used much, if at all. The Stock Ferrule is a correct Type 2, 3rd Variation with round shoulders and a large hole. The Lower Band is a correct Type 2 Stamped with arched profile. The butt trap compartment contains its original Type 2 Plastic Oiler with the pull through (and hole in the plastic cap) and lubricating oil section as well as original grease pot (still with grease) and original Type 2B Combination Tool. The rifle also comes with an original WWII steel claw Model 1907 Leather Sling that is dated 1943 although it is hard to make out the maker's name. The sling is still supple and solid. This is a beautiful WWII M1 Garand that is in exactly the same condition it was in 1943 when it was made.. Email me if you got any question, Thank you

title: For Sale:
For Sale:  Replica Colt 1851 Navy, CVA/ASM - super polished shiny! Blackpowder
postcontent:
This was a kit gun that I purchased a few years ago and spiffied up. It was originally naked steel with the grips you see, partially constructed. I went through the gun with a fine-toothed comb, sanded/polished every surface until it gleamed, shot it a few dozen times, cleaned it an put it away.

As you can see from the photos, the gun gleams in the light. The overall polishing is not 100% consistent as I used a Dremel-like tool and did all of the work by hand, but she's a 10 at 3 feet. It's only when you look super close that you see some inconsistencies.

Shoots great, rotates perfectly, ZERO rust or pitting in the barrel, and I challenge you to find a spec of rust on any component :).
